1. SUMMARY
Daandine-12 was spudded by Arrow Energy in mid February and completed at the
start of March 2006. Arrow utilised Johnson Drilling Rig 5 to drill and complete the
well. Daandine-12 was drilled as a development well for the Daandine Coal Seam
Gas (CSG) Development project. Daandine-12 reached a depth of 31Om and
finished in the lower Argyle coals.
10" Surface casing was set at 15Om within the lower Macalister. The well was then
drilled using a 9 7/8" PCD bit using formation water as the drilling fluid to a total
depth of 31Om within the lower Argyle coals. The well was firstly drilled to 292.6m
and then wireline logged. However after an inspection of the logs it was decided to
drill further to 31Om. A 16" under-reamer was used on the coal intervals to prevent
formation damage and increase the surface area of the producing coals. After
under reaming the well was flow tested and the flow rate was 11.5 L/s. In total the
well intersected 11.49m with 7.97m of net coal within the Wambo/lona/Argyle
production zone. The well was then completed with slotted casing across the coal
zones with blank 6 5/8" casing across the non-coal strata. The annulus was then
gravel packed to allow water and gas to flow and to maintain well bore stability.
A final water flow test of 8 L/s was recorded from the well.

3. GEOLOGY
3.1 REASON TO DRILL
Daandine-12 was drilled as a production well for the Daandine CSG Development

3. 2. STRATIGRAPHY AND TECTONIC SETTING
The Surat Basin is a large intracratonic basin of Mesozoic age covering
approximately 300,000km of southeastern Queensland and northern New South
Wales. The basin forms part of the larger Great Australian Basin (Green at al, 1997),
interfingering westward across the Nebine Ridge with the Eromanga Basin, and
eastward across the Kumbarilla Ridge with the Clarence-Moreton Basin (Exon,
1976). Basin Blocks consisting of the Central West Fold Belt and the New England
Fold Belt limit the basin to the south, while in the north the basin unconformably
overlies Triassic and Permian sediments of the Bowen Basin.
The Surat Basin contains up to 2,500m of sedimentary rocks deposited during the
later Triassic to Early Cretaceous periods (Figure : 3). The succession in the basin
consists of five fining-upwards sedimentary cycles dominated by fluvio-lacustrine
deposits (Exon, 1976; Exon and Burger, 1981; Day et al, 1983). The lower part of each
cycle typically comprises coarse-grained mature sandstone, grading up into more
labile sandstone and siltstone, with mostly siltstone, mudstone and coal in the upper
part. In the Cretaceous, inundation of the land through an increase in sea level led
to deposition of predominantly coastal plain and shallow sediments in two cycles.
Structurally, the Surat Basin is relatively simple (Figure 4), with the area of
maximum deposition in the Mimosa Syncline, which overlies the thickest Permian-
Triassic rocks in the Taroom Trough of the underlying Bowen Basin (Day et al.,
1983). Major faulting within the basin predominantly mirrors basinal boundary
faults of the underlying Bowen Basin. There is substantial folding across the basin,
which is due to compaction and draping, as well as some rejuvenation of older pre-
Jurassic structures and faults. Formations outcrop along the northern erosional
boundary and dip gently to the south and southwest at less than 5%.
